# Engineering Standards

## Core Principle

Write code that another senior engineer could understand in five minutes.

Prefer readability over cleverness.

Optimize for maintainability.

Never optimize prematurely.

---

# General Rules

Always:

- Use explicit types.
- Use descriptive names.
- Write small functions.
- Keep files focused.
- Prefer composition over inheritance.
- Remove dead code immediately.
- Refactor duplication.

Never:

- Use magic numbers.
- Use global mutable state.
- Create circular dependencies.
- Leave commented-out code.
- Leave TODO or FIXME comments.
- Ignore compiler or lint errors.

---

# File Size

Soft Limits

Component: <250 lines

Page: <300 lines

Backend Module: <300 lines

Utility: <150 lines

Hard Limit

500 lines

If exceeded:

Refactor.

---

# Function Rules

One responsibility.

Prefer:

20–40 lines

Maximum:

75 lines

Maximum nesting:

3 levels

Prefer early returns.

Avoid else after return.

Example:

GOOD

if (!invoice) return null

processInvoice(invoice)

BAD

if (invoice) {
    ...
} else {
    ...
}

---

# Naming

Variables

camelCase

Functions

camelCase

Components

PascalCase

Classes

PascalCase

Constants

UPPER_SNAKE_CASE

Files

kebab-case

Database Tables

snake_case

---

# Folder Organization

Organize by business domain.

GOOD

verification/

reports/

audit/

payments/

upload/

BAD

helpers/

misc/

utils2/

commonStuff/

---

# Imports

Order

1 Standard library

2 Third-party

3 Internal packages

4 Relative imports

One blank line between groups.

Never use wildcard imports.

---

# Components

Components should:

Receive props.

Render UI.

Delegate business logic.

Never perform heavy calculations.

Never fetch unrelated data.

---

# React

Prefer:

Server Components

Use Client Components only when needed.

Use hooks only for:

UI state

Effects

Browser APIs

Do not use useEffect unnecessarily.

Avoid derived state.

---

# State Management

Priority

1 URL

2 Server

3 Local Component

4 Global

Avoid global state unless truly shared.

---

# API Design

REST only.

Predictable naming.

Examples

GET /reports

POST /upload

GET /findings/{id}

DELETE /audit/{id}

Never create RPC-style endpoints.

---

# Backend

Business logic

↓

Services

Database

↓

Repositories

Never put business logic inside routes.

Routes should remain thin.

---

# Database

Use migrations.

Foreign keys required.

Indexes for:

customer_id

subscription_id

invoice_id

created_at

Avoid duplicated data.

Normalize where reasonable.

---

# Error Handling

Never swallow exceptions.

Return useful errors.

Log unexpected failures.

User-facing messages should be simple.

Internal logs should be detailed.

---

# Logging

Log

Uploads

Validation

Verification

Payments

Errors

Never log

Passwords

Tokens

Secrets

Full payment data

---

# Validation

Validate

Input

Output

Database writes

API requests

Environment variables

Never trust user input.

---

# Environment Variables

Never hardcode:

Keys

URLs

Secrets

Passwords

Tokens

Always validate required env variables on startup.

---

# Async

Use async only when beneficial.

Await everything.

Never create orphan tasks.

Handle timeouts.

Retry transient failures.

---

# Performance

Avoid N+1 queries.

Batch operations.

Paginate tables.

Stream large CSV files when practical.

Cache only after measuring.

---

# Security

Escape user input.

Validate uploads.

Limit upload size.

Delete temporary files.

Never expose stack traces.

Never expose secrets.

---

# CSV Rules

Treat CSV as untrusted input.

Validate:

Encoding

Headers

Duplicates

Relationships

Date formats

Currency

Never process malformed rows directly.

---

# Verification Engine

Every rule must be:

Pure

Deterministic

Testable

Independent

Never allow one rule to modify another.

Every rule returns:

Rule ID

Finding

Evidence

Confidence

Monthly Leakage

Annual Leakage

Recommendation

Execution Time

---

# AI

AI assists.

AI never decides.

Allowed

Header mapping

Entity matching

Narratives

Recommendations

Forbidden

Leakage calculations

ARR calculations

Financial math

Evidence generation

Confidence scoring

---

# Testing

Every feature requires

Unit tests

Edge cases

Error cases

Happy path

Regression tests for verification rules.

---

# Comments

Write comments explaining WHY.

Never explain WHAT obvious code does.

GOOD

// Price catalog versions overlap; newest effective date wins.

BAD

// Increment i

---

# Git

One feature per commit.

Small pull requests.

Never mix refactoring with feature work.

Commit examples

feat: csv upload

feat: verification engine

feat: report generation

fix: duplicate coupon detection

refactor: report service

---

# Documentation

Whenever architecture changes:

Update docs.

Documentation is part of the implementation.

Never let docs drift.

---

# Definition of Quality

Before considering code complete:

✓ Types pass

✓ Lint passes

✓ Tests pass

✓ Responsive

✓ Accessible

✓ Loading state

✓ Empty state

✓ Error state

✓ Documentation updated

✓ No dead code

✓ No duplicated logic

✓ No console logging

---

# Decision Framework

When multiple implementations exist:

Choose the solution that is:

1 Most deterministic

2 Simplest

3 Most maintainable

4 Most testable

5 Most extensible

Never choose clever over clear.

---

# Engineering Goal

Every line of code should contribute toward one outcome:

Transform raw customer billing data into trustworthy, evidence-backed revenue leakage findings that a CFO can immediately understand and act on.

If code does not directly improve that outcome, question whether it belongs in the MVP.